  "updated_summary": "The Host, clad in a HEXCLAD polo, initiated the segment by comparing Hexclad cookware to the 'Rolls Royce of cars' while addressing a murmuring crowd. Chef Albert, focused at his blue-tiled station, meticulously chopped onions and mushrooms, explaining his process. The Host's interjection, \"That ain't gonna work!\" was followed by praise for Albert's culinary skills, eliciting cheers from the crowd. Albert confirmed he was preparing a 'Beef Wellington' sandwich, surprising the Host with the ambitious timeline. As 'ALBERT'S SANDWICH BEEF WELLINGTON' text overlay appeared, Albert stated, \"I make a sandwich,\" and confidently assured the Host, \"They will see. Easy, easy.\" The Host then turned to Chef Owen, intensely chopping red onions at a yellow-tiled station, acknowledging Owen's determination to win. The competition intensified with a split-screen showing Chef Owen chopping and Chef Salt Hank sautéing, while the Host bantered with the chefs and engaged the crowd behind metal barricades. Close-ups revealed Salt Hank adding mustard to seared meat and Owen adding oil to onions, accompanied by chopping and sizzling sounds. With \"NINE minutes to go!\" announced, Salt Hank sautéed and added mustard to seared meat, aiming to assemble his sandwich, while Albert worried about time while making pickled onions and chilies. Owen reported he was doing \"really well,\" as 'Puff Pastry' and specific sandwich text overlays appeared. The Host declared, \"FIVE minutes remaining!\" and later, \"Three and a half minutes to go!\" as Owen detailed his sauce ingredients. As time dwindled, with \"6 Minutes Still Remain\" and \"30 seconds to go!\" overlays, Albert was declared \"done\" with five minutes left, and encouraged to \"tart that thing up.\" Owen worked to melt cheese, describing his quick pickle and sauce components. Salt Hank was asked to baste his \"still rare\" meat, with a 'SALT HANK'S SANDWICH FRENCH DIP' overlay appearing. The Host emphasized presentation in the \"final seconds,\" calling it a \"make or break situation,\" and rallied the crowd and chefs with \"60 seconds to go, guys!\" The 'idiot SANDWICH' sign remained prominent throughout the fast-paced cooking actions, sizzling pans, chopping, and seasoning, interspersed with wide shots of the lively crowd and colorful cooking stations."
